    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "64065a93_08509927",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 210,
      "author": {
        "id": 1109829
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-11T13:37:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t understand why this is better than making this a method on a \"fetchOperation\" type. In either case, the user has to reference the struct to see what\u0027s in it and (in this case) note that passing by value is just an expensive no-op.\n\nI don\u0027t care enough to block the CL on this, but the entire *point* of methods on objects is that you have an object with state/data and methods that manipulate that state/data. That is the case here, and I think not embracing it reduces both the readability of the code.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 210,
        "startChar": 79,
        "endLine": 210,
        "endChar": 97
      },
      "revId": "dee5be7a6abbab2c19ff5751b47e13641b2de3be",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "959e00c5_fdef08a1",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 210,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002080
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-14T21:02:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "If fetchOnce changes the underlying state of its receiver, it\u0027d look like this:\n\ntype fetchOperation struct {...}\n\nfunc (o *fetchOperation) fetch()\nfunc (o *fetchOperation) fetchOnce()\n\nfetchOnce() makes some modification to the struct, but without reading the entire function, it\u0027s more difficult for a reader to reason about the entire set of state changes that occurs when any of the methods are called.  This is the main reason I dislike using the operations struct + method state change patterns.\n\nIn this code, it\u0027s fairly clear that fetchOnce:\n* Writes into a channel\n* Fetches at an index\n* Returns another index\n* Make no other state changes (except it might modify params.lst, not super thrilled about that, but oh well).\n\nAlso IIUC in go, due to how the GC works, passing by pointer could actually be more expensive, so I don\u0027t think it\u0027s necessarily safe to say passing by pointer is always cheaper.",
      "parentUuid": "64065a93_08509927",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 210,
        "startChar": 79,
        "endLine": 210,
        "endChar": 97
      },
      "revId": "dee5be7a6abbab2c19ff5751b47e13641b2de3be",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
